Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Original Code | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | ASP.NET request termination | Remove; return from action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Request termination + redirect | Return `Redirect(url)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | TAE as control flow | Remove entirely |

## Migrated ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Controller

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST: /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // In ASP.NET Core, return a FileResult — no Response.Clear/End needed.
        // The framework handles Content-Disposition and terminates the response.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    // POST: /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Returning Redirect() does NOT call Thread.Abort.
            // It sets a 302 status and the framework ends the response normally.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) needed — it doesn't exist in .NET 8.
        // OperationCanceledException is the modern equivalent if you need
        // to handle client disconnects (see pitfall note below).
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls for This Migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Response.End()` doesn't exist** | In .NET 8 it throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Return an `IActionResult` instead — the framework handles flushing and closing the response. |
| **`Response.Redirect(url, true)` — the `true` is the problem** | The `endResponse: true` param called `Thread.Abort` internally. In ASP.NET Core, `Redirect()` returns a result object — execution continues past it, so **don't put code after `return Redirect()`** that you don't want to run. |
| **Swallowed `ThreadAbortException` hid bugs** | The old `catch (ThreadAbortException) {}` block could mask real issues. In the migrated code, exceptions propagate naturally. If `ProcessRequest()` can be cancelled by client disconnect, catch `OperationCanceledException` explicitly — but **don't swallow it** unless you have a specific recovery action. |
| **`Response.Write` + manual headers → `File()` result** | Don't manually write to `HttpResponse.Body` for file downloads. Use `File()`, `PhysicalFile()`, or `FileStreamResult` — they handle headers, buffering, and content-length correctly. |
| **`User.Identity` can be null** | In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` may be null if no auth middleware is configured. Use null-conditional (`?.IsAuthenticated ?? true`) or add `[Authorize]`. |

## If `ProcessRequest()` is long-running

Wire up `HttpContext.RequestAborted` so client disconnects cancel work:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> RedirectAfterProcess()
{
    if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        return Redirect("/login");

    try
    {
        // Pass the cancellation token through the full call chain
        await ProcessRequestAsync(HttpContext.RequestAborted);
        return Redirect("/success");
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException)
    {
        // Client disconnected — log and return 499 or similar
        return StatusCode(499);
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        LogError(ex);
        return Redirect("/error");
    }
}
```

This replaces the old `Thread.Abort`-based request termination with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.
